               "id": "planets",
               "text": "<p><h3>Formation of Planets</h3>Planets originate from clouds of dust (<htcite0> ; <htcite1>). As the formation process commences, these particles are initially minuscule in size (<htcite2> ; <htcite3>). As the cloud begins to collapse under gravitational forces, the dust grains gradually coalesce and collide, eventually forming larger structures known as planetesimals (<htcite4>).</p><p class=\"lab\"><b>Practice 1: Creating planetesimals</b><br />Place a few grains, such as sand or beans, on top of a piece of paper. Ensure they are spaced apart.<br />Although not visible, the paper and the space around, representing the cosmic space, contains more gas than grains.<br />Slowly begin to move and fold the paper until the grains come together, forming your own planetesimal.<br />When they grains are together, you have your \"planetesimal\".</p><p>Before proceeding further, it's essential to note a key observation: conventional teaching suggests that gravity attracts matter based on the mass of the object. However, this principle does not hold true for all known models, as explained by by Sabine Hossenfelder (<htcite5> ; <htcite6>) and Dr. Don Lincoln (<htcite7>), and Quantum Fracture (<htcite8>).</p><p>The planetesimal continues to attract particles, gradually forming a larger structure known as a protoplanet. Over time, through a slow accretion process, the protoplanet accumulates more matter until it reaches the status of a fully-fledged planet (<htcite9>).</p><p>While there is a general consensus on the process of planetary formation, recent discussions have led to modifications in the definition of a planet to: an object of sufficient size, rounded by its gravitational orbit around a star, capable of gravitationally clearing its orbital neighborhood of other celestial objects (<htcite10> ; <htcite11>).</p>",
