               "id": "molecule",
               "text": "<p><h3>Molecules</h3>Planetesimals form through the collision and aggregation of small grains, eventually evolving into massive structures. However, amidst these processes lies an intermediate stage that remains unexplored: molecules.</p><p>Molecules consist of two or more atoms bonded together to form a pure substance, capable of retaining its chemical properties even when divided (<htcite0>).</p><p>The first space-borne molecules likely occurred during the recombination period (<htcite1>), a phase characterized by the absence of dust grains but the presence of abundant atoms. This environment facilitated the formation of small molecules, including hydrogen molecules (H<sub>2</sub>) (<htcite2>).  Technological advancements have vastly improved our understanding of interstellar space, leading to the identification of over 170 different molecules that are also part of living beings, including essential compounds such as water (H<sub>2</sub>O), and ammonia (NH<sub>3</sub>) (<htcite3>).</p><p>Interestingly, some molecules integral to terrestrial lifeforms have also been detected beyond our planet's confines. Alongside water, various acids have been identified (<htcite4> ; <htcite5> ; <htcite6>). The transportation of these molecules to planets, potentially via comets (<htcite7>), could have played a pivotal role in facilitating the emergence of life.</p>",
