            {
               "id": "together",
               "text": "<p><h3>Grouping for life</h3>As inhabitants of this planet, we are comprised of a diverse array of molecules, much like the plants and animals that surround us. This observation, could lead us to the conclusion that with molecules and a planet we have life. If so, one might expect nearby planets to also support life. What are we missing?</p><p>Firstly, it is essential to delineate regions within stellar systems where life-supporting planets may exist. These areas, known as habitable zones, impose specific criteria for planetary habitability (<htcite0> ; <htcite1>): <ul><li>Presence of liquid water on the planet's surface (<htcite2>).</li><li>Composition of the planet, which must be rocky akin to Earth.</li><li>Adequate energy received from a star to maintain temperatures conducive to life as we know it.</li><li>Existence of natural processes such as tectonic activity that facilitate essential cycles of carbon and silicon (<htcite3>).</li></ul></p><p>Furthermore, it is imperative to recognize the correlation between habitable zones and the size of the host star (<htcite4>).</p><p>When a planet is formed in a <b>habitable zone</b>, the molecules to make the <b>life</b> in this planet can finally to group, but as Carl H. Gibson <i>et al.</i> highlight, the process to create life in the planet can be expanded to bigger horizons (<htcite5>): <ul><li>Precursors to life may originate within the centers of protogalaxies (<htcite6>).</li><li>Life may have arisen from \"seeds\" rather than from an \"inorganic soup\" for reasons of efficiency (<htcite7>).</li><li>The emergence of life via abiogenesis is not guaranteed (<htcite8>).</li> </ul></p><p>It is necessary to remember for the reader, that contradictions are part of the science, and we cannot discard completely the idea of an inorganic soup. Lena Vicente <i>et al.</i> studied different ways to test hypothesis to arise of the life (<htcite9>).</p><p>The timing of life's of emergence has direct relationship with the chosen model (<htcite10>). According to the HGD model, life emerged subsequent to the formation of protogalaxies (<htcite11>), whereas in the ΛCDMHC (<htcite12>), it happens more recently (<htcite13>). In the case of Earth, the advent of life occurred millions of years after the planet's formation (<htcite14>).</p>",
